<h2>HVAC Systems in West Virginia</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>West Virginia's continental climate creates distinct heating and cooling requirements that vary significantly by elevation and geographic location. The state experiences approximately 4,500-5,500 heating degree days annually, with higher elevations requiring substantially more heating energy. Cooling degree days range from 800-1,200 annually, indicating moderate air conditioning needs during summer months. This climate profile makes heating efficiency the primary concern for most homeowners, though cooling efficiency remains important for comfort and energy management during peak summer periods.</p>

<p>For optimal performance in West Virginia's climate, HVAC systems should prioritize high heating efficiency with adequate cooling capacity. Heat pumps are particularly well-suited for much of the state, offering both heating and cooling with superior efficiency compared to traditional systems. In areas with extreme winter temperatures, dual-fuel heat pump systems that switch to gas backup during very cold periods provide optimal comfort and efficiency. Recommended SEER ratings for cooling should be 16-18 for optimal efficiency without over-investing in cooling capacity that won't be fully utilized. HSPF ratings for heat pumps should be 9.0 or higher to ensure efficient heating performance.</p>

