<h2>West Virginia Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>West Virginia offers several financial incentives that make solar and HVAC investments more attractive for residential and commercial customers. The most significant incentive remains the federal Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work, potentially saving thousands of dollars on typical residential installations.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal Solar Investment Tax Credit (30%):</strong> Available through 2032, this credit can be applied against federal income taxes owed and covers the full cost of solar panel systems, inverters, mounting equipment, and installation labor. The credit can be carried forward to future tax years if it exceeds current year tax liability.</li>
<li><strong>Property Tax Exemption:</strong> West Virginia exempts solar energy systems from property tax assessments, meaning the added home value from solar installation won't increase annual property tax bills. This exemption applies to both the equipment and installation value.</li>
<li><strong>Appalachian Power Net Metering:</strong> Customers with solar systems up to 25kW can participate in net metering, receiving credit for excess electricity generation at the full retail rate. Credits roll over monthly and are paid out annually at avoided cost rates.</li>
<li><strong>Utility Rebate Programs:</strong> Appalachian Power and other utilities occasionally offer rebates for high-efficiency HVAC equipment, energy audits, and weatherization improvements. These programs vary by utility territory and available funding.</li>
<li><strong>USDA Rural Development Grants:</strong> Rural properties may qualify for USDA Rural Energy for America Program (REAP) grants covering up to 25% of renewable energy project costs, which can be combined with federal tax credits for maximum savings.</li>
</ul>

